Although considerable research has been conducted to better understand the stress
variables among Indian students, it remains unknown if this stress boosts academic performance
or negatively affects students' mental health and well-being.
Conclusion
Academic stress among Indian students continues to be a worrisome crisis for the
country. Pressure from schools due to a strict adherence to the curriculum has resulted in an
excessively competitive environment for students, affecting their health negatively. Numerous
private tuition classes, high rates of enrolment in coaching centers, excessive homework
provided by schools, and a daunting rat race to secure high positions in examinations has led to
schools being seen as an educative environment in which priority is given to passing
examinations, scoring a good university, and securing a high-paying job, as opposed to
understanding concepts and bolstering creativity. The extreme competition has led parents to
force their children to study in the hope of securing a better academic future. With a national
lockdown in effect due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Indian school students have expressed
increased stress due to uncertainty in their academic future and inefficient learning via online
classes.
Moreover, the increased pressure comes alongside a drastic change in students' daily
routines and their ability to engage in coping strategies due to the nationwide lockdown. That
being said, students have started engaging in different coping methods at home to alleviate stress.
